# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rescript-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:rescript-lang/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM) together with a composable build system for OCaml (Dune).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml was developed first in the context of automated theorem proving, and is used in static analysis and formal methods software.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Beyond these areas, it has found use in systems programming, web development, and specific financial utilities, among other application domains.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The acronym *CAML* originally stood for *Categorical Abstract Machine Language*, but OCaml omits this abstract machine.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml is a free and open-source software project managed and principally maintained by the French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (Inria).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In the early 2000s, elements from OCaml were adopted by many languages, notably F# and Scala.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] ML-derived languages are best known for their static type systems and type-inferring compilers.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml unifies functional, imperative, and object-oriented programming under an ML-like type system.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Thus, programmers need not be highly familiar with the pure functional language paradigm to use OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] By requiring the programmer to work within the constraints of its static type system, OCaml eliminates many of the type-related runtime problems associated with dynamically typed languages.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Also, OCaml's type-inferring compiler greatly reduces the need for the manual type annotations that are required in most statically typed languages.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] For example, the data types of variables and the signatures of functions usually need not be declared explicitly, as they do in languages like Java and C#, because they can be inferred from the operators and other functions that are applied to the variables and other values in the code.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Effective use of OCaml's type system can require some sophistication on the part of a programmer, but this discipline is rewarded with reliable, high-performance software.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml is perhaps most distinguished from other languages with origins in academia by its emphasis on performance.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] These are rare enough that avoiding them is quite possible in practice.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Aside from type-checking overhead, functional programming languages are, in general, challenging to compile to efficient machine language code, due to issues such as the funarg problem.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Xavier Leroy has stated that "OCaml delivers at least 50% of the performance of a decent C compiler", although a direct comparison is impossible.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Some functions in the OCaml standard library are implemented with faster algorithms than equivalent functions in the standard libraries of other languages.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Between the 1970s and 1980s, Robin Milner, a British computer scientist and Turing Award winner, worked at the University of Edinburgh's Laboratory for Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Milner and others were working on theorem provers, which were historically developed in languages such as Lisp.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Milner repeatedly ran into the issue that the theorem provers would attempt to claim a proof was valid by putting non-proofs together.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] As a result, he went on to develop the meta language for his Logic for Computable Functions, a language that would only allow the writer to construct valid proofs with its polymorphic type system.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] ML was turned into a compiler to simplify using LCF on different machines, and, by the 1980s, was turned into a complete system of its own.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] ML would eventually serve as a basis for the creation of OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In the early 1980s, there were some developments that prompted INRIA's Formel team to become interested in the ML language.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Luca Cardelli, a research professor at University of Oxford, used his *functional abstract machine* to develop a faster implementation of ML, and Robin Milner proposed a new definition of ML to avoid divergence between various implementations.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Simultaneously, Pierre-Louis Curien, a senior researcher at Paris Diderot University, developed a calculus of categorical combinators and linked it to lambda calculus, which led to the definition of the *categorical abstract machine* (CAM).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Guy Cousineau, a researcher at Paris Diderot University, recognized that this could be applied as a compiling method for ML.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Caml was designed and developed first by INRIA's Formel team headed by Gérard Huet.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The first implementation of Caml was created in 1987 and was further developed until 1992.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Though it was spearheaded by Ascánder Suárez, Pierre Weis and Michel Mauny carried on with development after he left in 1988.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Guy Cousineau is quoted recalling that his experience with programming language implementation was initially very limited, and that there were multiple inadequacies for which he is responsible.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Between 1990 and 1991, Xavier Leroy designed a new implementation of Caml based on a bytecode interpreter written in C.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In addition to this, Damien Doligez wrote a memory management system, also known as a sequential garbage collector, for this implementation.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] This new implementation, known as Caml Light, replaced the old Caml implementation and ran on small desktop machines.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In the following years, libraries such as Michel Mauny's syntax manipulation tools appeared and helped promote the use of Caml in educational and research teams.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In 1995, Xavier Leroy released Caml Special Light, which was an improved version of Caml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] An optimizing native-code compiler was added to the bytecode compiler, which greatly increased performance to comparable levels with mainstream languages such as C++.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Also, Leroy designed a high-level module system inspired by the module system of Standard ML which provided powerful facilities for abstraction and parameterization and made larger-scale programs easier to build.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Didier Rémy and Jérôme Vouillon designed an expressive type system for objects and classes, which was integrated within Caml Special Light.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] This led to the emergence of the Objective Caml language, first released in 1996 and subsequently renamed to OCaml in 2011.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] This object system notably supported many prevalent object-oriented idioms in a statically type-safe way, while those same idioms caused unsoundness or required runtime checks in languages such as C++ or Java.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In 2000, Jacques Garrigue extended Objective Caml with multiple new features such as polymorphic methods, variants, and labeled and optional arguments.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Language improvements have been incrementally added for the last two decades to support the growing commercial and academic codebases in OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The OCaml 4.0 release in 2012 added Generalized Algebraic Data Types (GADTs) and first-class modules to increase the flexibility of the language.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The OCaml 5.0.0 release in 2022 is a complete rewrite of the language runtime, removing the global GC lock and adding effect handlers via delimited continuations.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] These changes enable support for shared-memory parallelism and color-blind concurrency, respectively.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml's development continued within the Cristal team at INRIA until 2005, when it was succeeded by the Gallium team.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Subsequently, Gallium was succeeded by the Cambium team in 2019.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] As of 2023, there are 23 core developers of the compiler distribution from a variety of organizations and 41 developers for the broader OCaml tooling and packaging ecosystem.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In 2023, the OCaml compiler was recognised with ACM SIGPLAN's Programming Languages Software Award.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml features a static type system, type inference, parametric polymorphism, tail recursion, pattern matching, first class lexical closures, functors (parametric modules), exception handling, effect handling, and incremental generational automatic garbage collection.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml is notable for extending ML-style type inference to an object system in a general-purpose language.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] This permits structural subtyping, where object types are compatible if their method signatures are compatible, regardless of their declared inheritance (an unusual feature in statically typed languages).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] A foreign function interface for linking to C primitives is provided, including language support for efficient numerical arrays in formats compatible with both C and Fortran.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml also supports creating libraries of OCaml functions that can be linked to a *main* program in C, so that an OCaml library can be distributed to C programmers who have no knowledge or installation of OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Although OCaml does not have a macro system as an indivisible part of the language (metaprogramming), i.e. built-in support for preprocessing, the OCaml platform does officially support a library for writing such preprocessors.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] These can be of two types: one that works at the source code level (as in C), and one that works on the Abstract Syntax Tree level.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The latter, which is called PPX, acronym for Pre-Processor eXtension, is the recommended one.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The native code compiler is available for many platforms, including Unix, Microsoft Windows, and Apple macOS.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The bytecode compiler supports operation on any 32- or 64-bit architecture when native code generation is not available, requiring only a C compiler.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml bytecode and native code programs can be written in a multithreaded style, with preemptive context switching.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml threads in the same domain execute by time sharing only.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] However, an OCaml program can contain several domains.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Snippets of OCaml code are most easily studied by entering them into the *top-level REPL*.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] This is an interactive OCaml session that prints the inferred types of resulting or defined expressions.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Code can then be entered at the "#" prompt.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml infers the type of the expression to be "int" (a machine-precision integer) and gives the result "7".
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The first argument to ocamlc, "hello.ml", specifies the source file to compile and the "-o hello" flag specifies the output file.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The `option` type constructor in OCaml, similar to the `Maybe` type in Haskell, augments a given data type to either return `Some` value of the given data type, or to return `None`.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] This is used to express that a value might or might not be present.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Lists are one of the fundamental datatypes in OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The following code example defines a recursive function *sum* that accepts one argument, *integers*, which is supposed to be a list of integers.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Note the keyword `rec` which denotes that the function is recursive.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The function recursively iterates over the given list of integers and provides a sum of the elements.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The *match* statement has similarities to C's switch element, though it is far more general.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Another way is to use standard fold function that works with lists.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] OCaml lends itself to concisely expressing recursive algorithms.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The following code example implements an algorithm similar to quicksort that sorts a list in increasing order.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Or using partial application of the >= operator.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The following program calculates the smallest number of people in a room for whom the probability of completely unique birthdays is less than 50% (the birthday problem, where for 1 person the probability is 365/365 (or 100%), for 2 it is 364/365, for 3 it is 364/365 × 363/365, etc.) (answer = 23).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The following code defines a Church encoding of natural numbers, with successor (succ) and addition (add).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] A Church numeral `n` is a higher-order function that accepts a function `f` and a value `x` and applies `f` to `x` exactly `n` times.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] To convert a Church numeral from a functional value to a string, we pass it a function that prepends the string `"S"` to its input and the constant string `"0"`.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The given example outputs the Church numeral for five as “SSSSS0”.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] A variety of libraries are directly accessible from OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] For example, OCaml has a built-in library for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] As the factorial function grows very rapidly, it quickly overflows machine-precision numbers (typically 32- or 64-bits).
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Thus, factorial is a suitable candidate for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The LablGL bindings to OpenGL are required.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Far more sophisticated, high-performance 2D and 3D graphical programs can be developed in OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Thanks to the use of OpenGL and OCaml, the resulting programs can be cross-platform, compiling without any changes on many major platforms.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The following code calculates the Fibonacci sequence of a number *n* inputted.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] It uses tail recursion and pattern matching.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Functions may take functions as input and return functions as result.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] For example, applying *twice* to a function *f* yields a function that applies *f* two times to its argument.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The function *twice* uses a type variable*'a* to indicate that it can be applied to any function *f* mapping from a type*'a* to itself, rather than only to *int->int* functions.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In particular, *twice* can even be applied to itself.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] MetaOCaml is a multi-stage programming extension of OCaml enabling incremental compiling of new machine code during runtime.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] Under some circumstances, significant speedups are possible using multistage programming, because more detailed information about the data to process is available at runtime than at the regular compile time, so the incremental compiler can optimize away many cases of condition checking, etc.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] The new function is automatically compiled.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] At least several dozen companies use OCaml to some degree.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] In the context of academic teaching and research, OCaml has a remarkable presence in computer science teaching programmes, both in universities and colleges.
[src:rescript-lang/ocaml] A list of educational resources and these teaching programmes can be found at ocaml.org.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] ReScript shares characteristics with its ancestors Reason and OCaml.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] It is a statically typed language with a sound type system, and it emphasizes functional programming.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] However, ReScript’s syntax has started to evolve away from OCaml and closer to JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] For example, it uses the same arithmetic operators for integers and floating point numbers (like JavaScript), while OCaml and Reason use separate operators.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] Since ReScript transpiles to JavaScript, it can access the entire JavaScript ecosystem.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] It can both call JavaScript functions and have its functions called from JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] It has direct language support for the React front-end web library, including JSX.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] ReScript traces its roots back to **BuckleScript**, a compiler that compiled OCaml to JavaScript, which was first released in 2016 by Bloomberg L.P.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] In the same year, the Reason programming language was released, which was an alternate syntax for OCaml that was more similar to JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] As both projects were influenced by JavaScript, Reason and BuckleScript soon became an integrated toolchain.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] However, the BuckleScript team and the Reason team had different priorities.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] The Reason team wanted to maintain compatibility with the OCaml ecosystem, while the BuckleScript team wanted to be able to change the syntax to give the best developer experience to JavaScript programmers.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] In 2020, BuckleScript introduced a new syntax that started to diverge from Reason.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] A month later, the BuckleScript team rebranded its toolchain to ReScript, to focus solely on the JavaScript ecosystem and essentially becoming its own language, distinct from Reason.
[src:rescript-lang/rescript] ReScript’s support for compiling OCaml ended with version 12, released in 2025.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:rescript-lang/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:rescript-lang/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:rescript-lang/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
